[
    {
        "content": "<p>What's the definition of a monomorphism in a (weak) 2-category?</p>",
        "id": 234289679,
        "sender_full_name": "Chetan Vuppulury",
        "timestamp": 1618303572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's the relevant nLab page, <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/n-monomorphism\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/n-monomorphism</a><br>\nTo summarise, if you have an n-category, there is a notion of m-mono for each <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 \\leq m \\leq n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.78041em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719400000000001em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>. In the 2-category of categories, the 0,1 and 2-monomorphisms are the equivalences, fully faithful and faithful functors respectively.</p>",
        "id": 234294592,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1618306153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>See also <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/michaelshulman/show/full+morphism\">https://ncatlab.org/michaelshulman/show/full+morphism</a><br>\nwhere you have some orthogonal notions defined (eso, eso and full respectively), allowing one to characterize fullness.</p>",
        "id": 234294858,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1618306286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aren't these for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\left(\\infty,1\\right) </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\">)</span></span></span></span></span>-categories? In a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 2 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>-category we have noninvertible <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 2 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>-morphisms, does that not change the definition?</p>",
        "id": 234296850,
        "sender_full_name": "Chetan Vuppulury",
        "timestamp": 1618307290
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I had to link to that page because I couldn't find a page about generic n-monos.</p>",
        "id": 234297345,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1618307551
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> explained them on ncatcafe somewhere, maybe he can point you to the right place. In any case, iirc you should be able to extract the definition you're looking for from the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>-category</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\infty,1)\\text{-category}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">-category</span></span></span></span></span> setting.</p>",
        "id": 234297744,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1618307752
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the answer is a bit more subtle, in the sense that the notion of monomorphism from 1-categories can also have different generalisations/weakenings that are not captured by the n-monomorphism hierarchy. In particular “1-monomorphisms” seem to generalise from</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: x \\to y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism if and only the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mo>∗</mo></msub><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f_*: \\mathrm{hom}(z,x) \\to \\mathrm{hom}(z,y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.175696em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> are <del>isomorphisms</del> injections of sets.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>to </p>\n<ul>\n<li>A morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: x \\to y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism if and only the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mo>∗</mo></msub><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f_*: \\mathrm{hom}(z,x) \\to \\mathrm{hom}(z,y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.175696em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> are (whatever the generalisation of injection to categories/higher categories/higher groupoids is, depending on the setting)</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 234300538,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618309170
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But one can also try to weaken the “elementary” definition, that is, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism if and only if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>h</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g;f = h;f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> implies that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g = h</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span></span></span></span>, more in the direction of 'formal higher category theory'. For example, one weakening that makes sense in 2-categories would be:</p>\n<p>“Every 2-isomorphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>g</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>≃</mo><mi>h</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha: g;f \\simeq h;f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> factors through a 2-isomorphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>β</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>≃</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\beta: g \\simeq h</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.65819em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span></span></span></span>.”</p>",
        "id": 234300896,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618309338
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And in the 2-category of categories, I think that corresponds to a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/pseudomonic+functor\">pseudomonic functor</a>, which is a functor that is <em>faithful</em> and <em>full on isomorphisms</em>.</p>",
        "id": 234300990,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618309406
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And that's not the same as a 1-monomorphism in the sense above, which corresponds to a full and faithful functor.</p>",
        "id": 234301077,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618309454
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So as for many similar questions, the answer is: “There is no single way to generalise this concept from categories to higher categories; you really have to look at the specific aspect that you are trying to capture, and find what works best.”</p>",
        "id": 234301437,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618309640
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276363\">Amar Hadzihasanovic</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/mono.20in.20a.202-category/near/234300538\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>A morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: x \\to y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span> is a monomorphism if and only the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mo>∗</mo></msub><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f_*: \\mathrm{hom}(z,x) \\to \\mathrm{hom}(z,y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.175696em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">h</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">m</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> are isomorphisms of sets.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think you mean \"injections of sets\".</p>",
        "id": 234335681,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1618324301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oops, of course.</p>",
        "id": 234348186,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618327690
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On second thought, the issue is probably not about what definition we are taking (the “representable” one or the “elementary” one), but rather about the fact that 'monomorphisms of sets' have different generalisations to (higher) categories/groupoids that induce different generalisations on arbitrary higher categories/groupoids via the “representable” definition.</p>",
        "id": 234349813,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1618328247
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"319282\">@Chetan Vuppulury</span> </p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/pseudomonic+morphism\">Pseudomonic morphism</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>may be what you want; it relies on the definition of \"pseudomonic functor\".</p>",
        "id": 234352383,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1618329186
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's true that there are many <em>factorization systems</em> on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-categories for large <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>, but I think only fully-faithful morphisms and pseudomonic morphisms really have a claim to be \"the\" notion of monomorphism for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-categories, since they're the only ones that specialize to monomorphisms of sets considered as discrete <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-categories.</p>",
        "id": 234367274,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1618334565
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general I think when there are noninvertible 2-cells around, fully-faithful morphisms are better-behaved than pseudomonic ones.  But the pseudomonic ones have their uses too.</p>",
        "id": 234367352,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1618334594
    }
]